04329nam a22004695i 9780804764148DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20201999cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047641487 a10.1515/97808047641482doi  a(DE-B1597)564021  a(OCoLC)1198930884  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a320.982/121 aAdelman, Jeremy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRepublic of Capital :bBuenos Aires and the Legal Transformation of the Atlantic World /cJeremy Adelman. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©1999  a1 online resource (392 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. Toward a Political History of Economic Life -- tSECTION I. The Age of Revolution, 1780's- 1820's -- t2. Imperial Reconstitution and the Limits of Political Property -- t3. The Quest for Equipoise in the Shadow of Revolution -- t4. From Revolution to Civil War -- t5. Rosas Agonistes, or the Political Economy of Cronyism -- t6. Chains of Obligation: The Duress of Merchant Law -- t7. Reconsidering the Republic -- t8. Constitutional Persuasions -- t9. The New Property of Merchant Capital -- t10. Making Money: The Battle for Monetary Authority -- t11. The Unfinished Revolution of the Republic of Capital -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is a political history of economic life. Through a description of the convulsions of long-term change from colony to republic in Buenos Aires, Republic of Capital explores Atlantic world transformations in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries. Tracing the transition from colonial Natural Law to instrumental legal understandings of property, the book shows that the developments of constitutionalism and property law were more than coincidences: the polity shaped the rituals and practices arbitrating economic justice, while the crisis of property animated the support for a centralized and executive-dominated state. In dialectical fashion, politics shaped private law while the effort to formalize the domain of property directed the course of political struggles. In studying the legal and political foundations of Argentine capitalism, the author shows how merchants and capitalists coped with massive political upheaval and how political writers and intellectuals sought to forge a model of liberal republicanism. Among the topics examined are the transformation of commercial law, the evolution of liberal political credos, and the saga of political and constitutional turmoil after the collapse of Spanish authority. By the end of the nineteenth century, statemakers, capitalists, and liberal intellectuals settled on a model of political economy that aimed for open markets but closed the polity to widespread participation. The author concludes by exploring the long-term consequences of nineteenth-century statehood for the following century's efforts to promote sustained economic growth and democratize the political arena, and argues that many of Argentina's recent problems can be traced back to the framework and foundations of Argentine statehood in the nineteenth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z978311070421140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476414840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804764148423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804764148.jpg  a978-3-11-070421-1  SUP eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles